[1] China: 21st human case confirmed
Date: Mon 14 Aug 2006
From: Mary Marshall <tropical.forestry@btinternet.com>
Source: Yahoo News, Agence France Presse report, Mon 14 Aug 2006 [edited]
[URL arrived garbled - Mod.JW]

China: 14th bird flu fatality confirmed
-------------------------------------------
The Health Ministry has confirmed China's 14th human fatality from
bird flu; a 62-year-old man who died last month [July 2006]. The
patient, a farmer, was from Jimsar county in the northwest region of
Xinjiang, the Ministry said in a statement on its website on Monday
[14 Aug 2006]. It said the man fell ill on 19 Jun 2006 and died on 12
Jul 2006 and that initial laboratory tests aimed at checking whether
he had succumbed to the H5N1 avian flu virus had been inconclusive.
For one month before falling ill, the man did not have close contact
with any human cases of bird flu, and there was no evidence he had
been near sick or dead poultry, the Ministry said. "There was no
confirmed link to poultry, but that doesn't mean there wasn't any
contact," said Roy Wadia, a Beijing-based spokesman for the World
Health Organization. "Most of the cases on the Chinese mainland have
not had any confirmed link to poultry," he said.
The county the patient was from is 150 km (94 miles) east of the
Xinjiang capital Urumqi. "There have been outbreaks in Xinjiang close
to Urumqi in the last couple of years, so the area is not new to
poultry outbreaks," said Wadia. He declined to speculate on whether
the patient was more likely to have caught the virus from
domesticated poultry or migratory birds. "Migratory birds fly across
of much of China, including Xinjiang," he said. "Everything is possible."
People who had been in contact with the deceased patient have been
placed under observation, the Ministry said. He is the 21st human
patient to be confirmed by China's health authorities. The
announcement came shortly after China said its 1st human bird flu
victim was in late 2003, 2 years earlier than previously reported.
While Beijing denied any cover-up, the confirmation of the 2003 case
was believed likely to change the time frame for the current outbreak
of the disease regionally. Up till then, the 1st reported signs in
Asia of the H5N1 virus were poultry deaths in South Korea in late 2003.
--
