[3] China: 21st human case confirmed
Date: Mon 14 Aug 2006
From: Marianne Hopp <mjhopp12@yahoo.com>
Source: World Health Organization (WHO), CSR, Disease Outbreak News,
Mon 14 Aug 2006 [edited]
<http://www.who.int/csr/don/2006_08_14/en/index.html>

China: Avian influenza Situation - WHO update 14
-----------------------------------------------
As of Mon 14 Aug 2006, the Ministry of Health in China has confirmed
the country's 21st case of human infection with the H5N1 avian influenza virus.
The case occurred in a 62-year-old male farmer from the northwestern
province of Xinjiang. He developed symptoms on 19 Jun and died on 12
Jul 2006. Initial tests on patient specimens produced negative
results. As a precautionary measure, tests were repeated during July
and August 2006 and eventually produced positive results, which were
confirmed today [14 Aug 2006] by the Ministry of Health.
An epidemiological investigation of the case was unable to uncover a
history of exposure to dead or diseased birds. The man had no history
of travel during the month prior to symptom onset. No recent poultry
outbreaks have been reported in the vicinity of the man's home.
Xinjiang Province had not previously reported a human case.
Of the 21 cases confirmed to date in China, 14 have been fatal.
--
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
[There is a lack of consistency about the prevalence of disease in
poultry in the Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous Region, but the case
described above is the 1st human case in the region. A map of the
Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous Region of China can be viewed at
<http://www.maps-of-china.com/xinjiang-s-ow.shtml>.
